eventData.headline: Yale Student Energy Association
eventData.description:
The Yale Student Energy Association is Yale’s premier student-run energy club. The club addresses issues ranging from new solar technologies to carbon capture and sequestration to nuclear fusion, and provides students with an opportunity to learn from the very best in the field through the Lecture series and first-hand opportunities to lead an initiative that would impact Yale’s community.

Are you interested in learning more about where your laptop’s power comes from? Do you have an idea that could change the way we perceive energy and use it more sustainably? Do you want to create an immediate impact at Yale and improve the relationship and awareness of energy issues? If your answer to any of these questions is “yes”, then join us for a discussion of the student aspects of Energy@Yale.

The sessions will include explanations about Yale Student Energy Association, Yale’s premier undergraduate energy group, the Yale Energy Alliance, the umbrella group for everything energy, and the Student Energy Consortium, the national intercollegiate network for energy activities. We will also be happy to entertain questions about activities/events, academic pathways, and career pathways in energy from a student’s point of view. Can’t wait to see you all!

eventData.headline: Party of the Left
eventData.description:
Yale’s oldest leftist debating society dedicated to the most pressing political and philosophical questions facing the contemporary left.

R: Mandate the Vaccine
Should we require people to take the vaccine? How do we reconcile public health with bodily autonomy? Come discuss these questions with us as we debate R: Mandate the vaccine and debate public health policy in a pandemic.

eventData.headline: Guild of Carillonneurs
eventData.description:
We play the bells in Harkness Tower. Learn to play the carillon from current members of the Guild, and join us in serenading the Yale campus twice a day. We also offer lessons from visiting masterclass guests, as well as touring opportunities to play carillons all over the USA, as well as in Europe! We love big bells, and we hope you do too.

Come hang out with our members over zoom, talk about how to join, and maybe play some games!

eventData.headline: United Church of Westville
eventData.description:
UCW is a student-led, Christ-centered family committed to pursuing Christ. We focus on fostering unity in the Body by promoting discipleship and living in community with love and grace, making Christ known in both word and deed. As a Church, we strive to practice the indiscriminate love of God on Yale's campus. (https://www.ucw-yale.com/)

Come and hang out with UCW! We'll introduce our church and have a casual night of games.

eventData.headline: Yale Drama Coalition
eventData.description:
The Yale Drama Coalition (YDC) is an umbrella organization for theatre here at Yale. Our mission is to work with community members and the Yale administration to promote accessibility, fairness, and community within the theatre scene. You can also find us running Yale's Collaborative Arts Matching Program (CAMP) and hosting some very chaotic trivia nights!

Interested in getting involved in theatre but have no idea where to start? Have more specific questions about acting, directing, and everything in between? Want to find out what theaters on campus are DEFINITELY haunted? Come chat with the YDC about all things Yale theatre!

eventData.headline: NROTC Undergraduate Association
eventData.description:
The Naval Reserve Officers Training Corps (NROTC) Program was established to educate and train qualified young men and women for service as commissioned officers in the US Navy (unrestricted line), or in the Marine Corps. As the largest single source of Navy and Marine Corps officers, the NROTC Scholarship Program fills a vital need in preparing mature young men and women for leadership and management positions in an increasingly technical Navy and Marine Corps.

Speak with Midshipmen about life as a member of Yale NROTC, benefits of the program, and. careers in the Navy and USMC.

eventData.headline: Chinese Adopted Siblings Program
eventData.description:
A joint project of the Chinese American Students Association (CASA) and the Taiwanese American Society (TAS), CASPY is a bi-annual cultural event held on Yale’s campus that seeks to inform Chinese adoptees and their parents about Chinese culture. Two times a year, in the spring and the fall, we invite you to join us for a full day of fun activities and events in our Kids, Teens, and Parent Programs.

Participating children are paired with Yale “Big Sibs” and placed into the Kids and Teens Programs. Highlights from past programs include Night Market with games and prizes, Calligraphy Workshop with Professor Su Wei, and different culinary activities with delicious food. Parents attend meaningful panels and discussions to connect with each other and to explore the many faceted topics surrounding adoption.

Into session for Yale's Chinese Adopted Siblings Program for Youth. We will introduce our biannual CASPY Day event for Chinese-born transracial adoptees in the tri-state area and follow with an open discussion for the Asian-American transracial community at Yale. Discussion topics will include identity building for Asian Americans, particularly for adoptees, as well as conflicts (cultural, mental, familial) that may arise while learning about oneself.
